print_settings.Notes:: To get the multi-color effect that I demonstrated, you need to swap out the material to a different color twice during the print. When the printer starts to print the very bottom of the triangle, stop the print and swap to a different color. After that, there will be an area where the chamfer on the top starts to form. After that, you can swap the material color once more. The longer you wait, the thicker the outline will be. Just make sure to swap out the color before it finishes the final layer, or else you'll only have 2 colors!

Notes:

To get the multi-color effect that I demonstrated, you need to swap out the material to a different color twice during the print. When the printer starts to print the very bottom of the triangle, stop the print and swap to a different color. After that, there will be an area where the chamfer on the top starts to form. After that, you can swap the material color once more. The longer you wait, the thicker the outline will be. Just make sure to swap out the color before it finishes the final layer, or else you'll only have 2 colors!

author: 2c2know

description.text:
Hi makers,

I thought you may like this puzzle, unfortunatly you will know it's secret but it's still a very puzzling puzzle which I am sure you will all enjoy.

Print with minimum 100 micron layer height with about 20% infill. I use 3 outer shells and 6 top and bottom layers at 100 micron. The tollerances are quite tight so you need to have your printer dialed in. You will also need a 4mm dia 2mm thick disc magnet and a ~9mm pin (I used a section of an m4 screw cut and sanded to length). The disc magent is placed in the base, its a snugg fit so no need to glue but you can if you need to, and the m4 pin in the top section. Make sure this moves freely and does not stick out before you assemble it, otherwise you may struggle to get it apart.

Assembly is not difficult but you will need to offer the parts together at an unnatural angle (you will see what I mean).

Hope you enjoy this make.

Pozzy 2017

title: Unregulated Box Mod (WIP)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
WOAH HEY WHAT ARE YOU DOING HERE? Why are you looking at this? I've completely abandoned this and moved on to different projects. If this looks cool, go look at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2756007

Update 5/2/17: I'm probably going to redo the design to make it more 3d printer friendly.

This is a work in progress, and I do not expect anyone to print this right now. I'd almost say don't print this at all since I'm not done. This upload is only here to show off what I'm working on and to get some feedback.

My buddies and I used to create box mods in Altoids tins back in freshman year of college. I had thought about designing and printing one for awhile and decided to go ahead and do it.

Biggest challenges I'm facing:
-Battery contacts
-Battery and battery door fitment
-Ergonomics

The battery contacts are meant to be made with thin sheets of copper, but aluminum foil would work as well (I imagine). I know I can buy battery sled and even just the contacts themselves, but I wanted to try my hand at making them from copper to save money potentially.

The battery door starts life as a solid model with no vents. This way, I can add whatever design I choose. I have many other variations of the door (the one shown is mine) and I will upload the rest once the project comes closer to completion. The tolerance for door fitment on the device is tight. I shaved material off of the door to make it go on but it's still tight. I made have to rethink and rework the design. Any suggestions here are appreciated.

The box was made with that rounded side to improve ergonomics but I had missed a few key points. The box is very small and a little awkward to hold because of this. I recommend having small hands to use this. The other issue is the sharp corners on the other side of the box. This issue can very easily be rectified.

The parts used to complete the box are:
-Low profile 510 connector (22mm)
-Momentary Switch (12mm)
-Mosfet (IRLB3034PBF)
-15k Ohm resistor
-Wire and shrink wrap tubing
-Copper sheets (Brass or aluminum would work fine)

Printer:

Alunar m506 (anet a6)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

20%

Notes:

70mm/s
Took 4.xx hours
The supports are a pain to remove.

Designed by making a model of every part I would need to create a vaporizer, then I made a shell around it in 123D. I then looked for possible problem areas and create 3 variations. OpenPV_v4 was the point where I said "Looks good. Let's print this puppy!"

title: XL650 adapter for Lee Funnel Case Collator

description.text:
This is an adapter to allow use of the (inexpensive) Lee funnel case collator with the Dillon XL650, and perhaps other Dillon progressive presses.

It snaps on the outside of a standard Dillon case feeder tube, and uses a 1/4 x 3" bolt with two nuts to hold the funnel assembly above the tube so you can load up the funnel tubes and turn them to drop cases as you go.

I steady the funnel with the plastic tube clip that came with the machine, presumably for the expensive mechanical collator they sell. A purpose built arm with a collar that goes around the tubes would probably work well, but I've never bothered to make one.

Sketchup files included if you need to embiggen it.

Printer:

MakerFarm

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.30

Infill:

40

Notes:

One of my first ever prints, I don't remember much about it.

Snap on Dillon drop tube, put bolt and nut in funnel assembly and put bolt down through the adapter small side. If it slides on adapter, you might need another nut on the top of the adapter to keep it high enough to spin over drop tube.

comments.text: Hello. Good job. Do you have any idea to fix plastic tunnels to the press?

description.text:
I really wanted to be able to use Triffidhunter's parametric herringbone gears ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10707 ) as recommended by Richrap, but they were just too tall to fit on my X-carriage.
This adapter will raise the Wade's block by 2 mm which is just enough to allow the large gear to fit.
Read more at http://mynext3dprinter.tumblr.com

Print the adapter and the herringbone gears.
I had to trim my prototype to clear the X belt. The modified STL file should fit perfectly.
Replace the old gears in the Mendel90 with shiny new ones.
Don't forget to recalibrate your Z-height and E steps/mm.

description.text: Wall mount (3M stickers will hold well) Toothpaste holder for bathroom.

This is a mod designed to separate the mainboard from the cabinet and force cool the mainboard and cpu of the UP mini using an external fan. Given the internal temperature of the chamber, the cooler we can keep the electronics the better.
The mod does not alter the printer in any way and all parts are designed to slide fit onto existing internal parts and the fan attaches with double sided tape.
The fan unit is a 40x40mm 12v version with a dust filter fitted to the inlet.
I have just uploaded a duct to suit an standard 80x80mm computer fan for those who do not have access to the smaller fan.. The 80mm fan however is untested. 120mm fan duct supplied also but I need to draw up another spool holder to keep it away from the duct

Print all 4 parts. The fan duct is attached to the lower grille on the mini by foam double sided tape. I am using a 12v external power source at the moment. There is a 5v header on the mainboard but I have not investigated this any further.
The cowlings all have a 1mm slot in them that slide over the metal support back pane that the mainbard attaches to. It will take a little support as they are an interference fit. The top cowling is fitted first and pushed home. Then the lower cowling and upper cowlings are fitted. These slide onto the back pane but also are notched to they join together and into the to cowling.

I was looking for a way to store glasses in my Jeep.

I needed something for two pairs of glasses because I don't normally wear glasses when I'm not driving. I have two pairs of identical frames, one pair with tinted lenses and the other with clear glass lenses. This made it easier as I was able to make both sides of the design the same.

This is a remix of the Tesla Drawer. It was necessary for me to move the notches for the arms to the end of the slots. Then I duplicated and flipped the part. I used TinkerCad to modify the STL file.

Edit in TinkerCAD: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/9UpkwRDjP0G

Please note that I left the object in TinkerCAD is in 2 parts to allow it be edited more easily. It can still be exported as a single STL without grouping the parts together.

I mounted the tray using 3M Dual Lock. It is a very strong plastic type of velcro-like material.

title: Elevation model of Dunedin, New Zealand.

description.text:
Elevation model of Dunedin, New Zealand. Created using University of Otago School of Surveying 15m DEM.
[UPDATED 4-2017] Fixed aspect ratio on texture and model to make both square and remove distortion.

Made depth map using University of Otago School of Surveying 15m DEM. https://koordinates.com/supplier/university-of-otago-national-school-of-surveying/data/ Black= low elevation, white = high. Used displace function in Blender to create a 3D mesh using the elevation model.

comments.text: So cool. Would love this for Queenstown/Wanaka and Aoraki/Mt Cook. How would I make one?
comments.author: Bisjo612

comments.text: LINZ has the 8m data available as geotiff tiles on the website. QGIS (free) with DEmto3D (Stl) add-in lets you load the tile and save an area as STL. Big files though: STL of Kingston to Queenstown with the Remarks and Walter Peak is about 300Mb!
comments.author: Bisjo612

comments.text: Do you live in Dunedin? I've recently worked on a neat interactive involving 3D printed models and projected data. It will be on display at Otago Museum 21-28 Jan 2017.
comments.author: Bisjo612

comments.text: Hi, to make the model you can extract a square depth map from https://koordinates.com/publisher/university-of-otago-national-school-of-surveying/ . You might need to convert it to 8 bit greyscale for use in blender (or another 3d package) or download it in that format, if you can. GIS software can be pretty useful if you're doing something on the coast or need to stitch some of these images together (QGIS).
comments.author: Bisjo612

comments.text: Thanks heaps, yes I am in Dunedin and will definitely go check it out then :) I teach geography and these will be amazing to help with that
comments.author: lukeeast

comments.text: Hey, Looks awesome! Do you have a walk through how you did this? Been trying to do it with some chch lidar data and GIS software but my meshes have holes in them causing to fill in random valleys. Any Pointers? Cheers
comments.author: jimmy_chch

comments.text: Hi Jimmy, terribly sorry. I only just saw this comment. I can't remember getting an email notification. Hope your sorted out your model issues.
comments.author: jimmy_chch

description.text: This is the first thing I've created on my Prusa that I designed myself.  It's a geometric cuff made in OpenSCAD after getting frustrated at Sketchup.  I never knew that getting into 3D printing would turn me into a jewellery designer! ;-)

Download and print.
It printed without supports, although it had a few errors.  I haven't really tuned my bridge-printing yet, so if you know what you're doing, you can probably getting to print better.
The interior oval is 60mm x 48mm; if you need it in a different size you can scale it or edit the OpenSCAD source, although it's not fully parametric.
The faceting of the outside is noticeable in the print; I kind of like that, but if you wanted to get a smoother edge it should be easy enough to tweak the OpenSCAD (the outer face is made from a sphere intersected with a box)

print_settings.Notes:: Be sure to use 100% infill. I have honeycombed non-stressed areas internally.

description.text:
I like the Dean's Connectors for my LIPO RC batteries but find them difficult to get apart. This tool makes it very easy to unplug the connectors, even new ones that are very tight. As a bonus I incorporated a tool on the back end to unplug JST balance plugs that are used on many LIPO batteries.
For the Dean's Connector you will have to sand or file a very small bevel on one side of the connector pair. This small bevel is on the negative lead side (the small side) so that the tool can easily be positioned. You do not have to bevel both sides of the connector, I beveled the battery side on all my batteries. To use the tool I slide the "teeth" of the tool along the small side of the joined connector until I feel the bevel then a light squeeze opens the connector.
For the JST balance connector use the other end of the tool. You can grasp the connector just under the lip where the wires come out and pull. Eliminates strain on the wires. The tool works with batteries that have 3 or more cells.
The design uses a 3 mm x 12 mm machine screw with a nyloc nut. The spring is from a ball-point pen.
I printed in PLA with 100% fill. To save PLA I incorporated honeycomb in the handles where the stresses are minimal.
Note - The teeth on this tool are quite sharp and the handles give a lot of mechanical advantage so keep this away from anyone who might hurt themselves with it. If this is a problem you can sand down the point a bit but will have to make a slightly deeper bevel on the connector.
4/15/17 - Added printable spring and modified spring nubs on handles to accommodate printed spring. Slight change to profile of JST grabber at back of handle.

author: toadharbor

title: K8200 / 3DRAG Parallel Z-Axis Spindle Gear
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
--(dts.Text liegt bei)--
Next improvement for the Velleman K8200 3D-Printer, the Z-axis parallel spindle gear driven by the original motor. When I had noticed that the extension-arm extremly wobbles when the printer quickly changes directions, i realized that the missing Z-guidance on right site is responsible for that. So, the main target is to reduce/eliminate this wobbling. The upgrade was planned in concern to keep changes to the original as less as possible and to protect my/your purse ;-)) See printed result on the last image! Updates:
-Add extension_arm_guide.dxf : you can create your guide with your own fitting for a different nut. (extrude to 16 mm)
-Add belt_tensioner_right.stl : if you have a larger belt or something else, use this with second copy of idler pulleys. P.S.: All things were printed with the original hotend. No further upgrades are necessary to get the parts, but your printer should be set well ;-)

The right steering track rod is replaced by a control rod. Keep in mind, that this new spindle is of the same typ like the left one!!
In my case this is a TR8x1,5 precise-control-rod for CNC-engines i replaced formerly but you can use a normal srew rod M8 like the original one.
The left side spindel torque is transferd to the right side by a T5 Belt over two idler pulleys. Replace the steering rod holder on the
right side with new holder keeping ball bearings for the right spindle. The only challange is to get a closed T5-belt in defined length between 1060 till 1090 millimeters (in my case 1075 mm - send me a short message, i will respond with the link to my supplier). You can remove the lower angle brackets of the top cross bar to avoid loss of printing height. Attention: Check out the new max printing height and update this value to your printing software/firmware!! (In my case i lost only 6 millimeters)
Furter informations can be found in the german section on RepRap-Forum (http://forums.reprap.org) - search for "K8200" Time required to print the parts: ~3-4 h
Time required to assembly parts: ~2-3 h Additional Needs:
400 mm spindle (control rod) with 8mm diameter +
1x spindle-nut (both like left side - see note above!)
11x M3x10 / 4x M5x10 screws wih nut,
2x M8x30 screw with 2x nuts
10x M8 washers
4x 608 ball bearings
1075 mm closed T5-belt 6mm

comments.text: Some Things to improve:
comments.author: SchwertAs

comments.text: Thanks for your comment, indeed there are some improvements possible. But in your case, I suspect an over-tightened belt. It isn't necessary tightening the upper belt very strong. It is enough that the teeth do not skip, not more! The right spindle has only a function as a guidance...the hard work is already done by the left side! In my case this original construction works since 1 1/2 years without any problems
comments.author: SchwertAs

comments.text: Thanks indeed this is a issue. But high tension at belt was needed to prevent belt from sliding. The teeth of the pulley do not have the planned steepness after printing. So I now constructed a pulley with more steepness at the teeth. I used 30 degree instead of 40 degree defined by the belt. Hope this prevents belt from sliding at lower spanner force.

remixed_from.title: Delving Decor: Dwarven Loot Markers (28mm/Heroic scale)

description.text:
I needed some treasure tokens and I wanted to create a consistent set, with same bases and such.

Here's where each item came from:

  • Armor 1 -Stockto's armored warrior. I posed him and chopped it down to size. Then created an armor rack.
  • Armor 2 - Same as above but without a helmet
  • Chest 1 - Dutch Mogul's loot markers
  • Chest 2 - Dutch Mogul's dwarven loot markers
  • Chest 3 (Didn't include) From Rocket Pig Games, only just noticed that they don't allow remixes in their license.
  • Chest and gold 1 - Tvalladon's 25mm Treasure Marker v2 - only modified the height of the base to match the rest - also cut in half and stood upright to give way way better printing result (z resolution is much better then y/x)
  • Coins - Dutch Mogul's loot markers - also cut in half and stood upright to give way way better printing result (z resolution is much better then y/x)
  • Sacks 1 - Dutch Moful's loot markers
  • Sacks 2 - Trynn's DnD Treasure Artifact
  • Ruined stone base - I created this to base other things I craft (the scrolls and the book) - also cut in half and stood upright to give way way better printing result (z resolution is much better then y/x)

The book was created using the process described by Josh Williamson on DM Scotty's Crafts N' Games facebook page. Since it's a closed group, I've replicated the tutorial with permission.

The scrolls used the process described by jenniferg in her scroll case

Other crafting bits:

  • Used woodland scenics snow flocking on most tokens
  • Added a sword, axe and a swarovski crystal to the chest + gold. The print came out poorly, but adding these elements it looks great

comments.text:
Yes. I haven't measured the vacuum though.
Things to make it work better
1) Use silicone sealer in both O ring slots between the body and the hose adapter.
2) I used #4 (M3) sheet metal screws to assemble.
3) Balance the impeller if possible.
4) The impeller and body needs to be as close together as possible.
5) It makes more noise then I like.

take a tube with a big diameter and test how much weight it can hold onto.
if the diameter is 35mm (10cm²) and it can hold 100g the pressure would equal -.01bar (to less for a vacuumtable).

description.text:
I bought this hotend https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B010MSTVZO and tried to install it using http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1777358 - the fan hit the top frame.

Next I tried http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1921269 but the mounting bracket wouldn't fit.

So I remixed it with http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1589653 to create this mount, then added the "thorped" fan http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1621937 - however the fan was sitting below the nozzle. I modified the mounting bracket to raise it up.

I cut the stock cable chain, soldered on the new heater and reused the stock thermistor.

To mount the extruder on the left frame I used http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1489794

Still dialing in the settings, I had to limit fan speed to 25%-50% and print at PLA at 230C to prevent under extrusion.

tag_height needs to be adjusted on changes on text_size and number of lines.

You might adjust border to a multiple of your printers nozzle diameter.

Have fun, create a customized version or post an I made one if you like.
The luggage tag is already spread all around the world.

description.text:
I did some mesh cleanup on the center piece. Added rounding on the top inner edge to make inserting the Osmo easier and to prevent scratches on the Osmo. Also added edge beveling on the base of the center support and on the edges of the leg bases where they join the body to give it a bit of a finished look.

I re-made the legs from scratch. The original legs were not completely square. I also added cutouts to reduce material and lighten them which should reduce print time as well.

I added 2 new legs with a 3 degree cant to them. This stand is nice if the surface is flat. Rarely the case though. By using a cant on the legs, the surface contact points are only out on the tips of the legs and not the whole bottom surface of the stand. I didn't do a cant on the z-axis leg.

description.text:
This version splits the mount into a base and cover. The base is glued with goop to the mini drak after cutting off the nose. The cover screws to the base with 3x m2.5 screws (about 10-12mm long is plenty. The hex nuts are captured in the base and should be glued in place to they don't slide away from the hole. I use nylon screws and nuts to minimize weight. Rev B moves the location of the split closer to the rear of the aircraft allowing both cameras to be removed through the front when the cover is unbolted from the base. You no longer need a large hole behind the foxeer camera, just a tunnel for the camera cable into the bay.

This mount is designed for the foxeer 1177 with 2.5 or 2.1mm lens (or any narrower lens will work too) and the runcam2.

The reversed files switch the orientation of the cameras (from the original design shown in the photos Edit: First two photos show the reversed prints as of 4-21-17) and puts the runcam2 on the right side of the plane. This makes it possible to remove the runcam2 rear cover without removing the runcam2 from the mount since the rear cover will slide towards the center of the bay to unlock.

Update 4/4/2017 Added cover with top support hole for airspeed sensor. It's designed for the MFD airspeed sensor which is just a single small 2.5mm dia tube (the static port is uncovered inside the aircraft in the new MFD airspeed sensor). But I left enough room that this hole can be drilled out for any diameter pitot and plenty of space for it to protrude so the side holes remain uncovered and still be ahead of the cover for uninterrupted airflow.

Update 4-26-17 Added 1pc file back for those that don't mind cutting enough foam to remove the cameras through the bay instead of having the bolted on front cover.

Update 5-3-17 Added 1pc file with 18mm hole for FPV cams such as the runcam swift.

Installation:

The foam cut is 17mm forward of the leading edge of the center bay cover indentation. Or 7mm forward of the leading end of the top fiberglass spar grooves. Be sure to cut perpendicular to the seam in the side of the fuse top to bottom. And keep it square when looking from the top or your cameras will be looking left or right.

Then you'll have to hog out a big square all the way into the bay to provide clearance for the runcam2 best to use a flat razor for this and be sure to keep the 7 degree angle (by eye is good enough) You can also put a hole through the top of the bay lip (just under the cover) on the forward right side to access the runcam2 power button. You'll be able to figure the location when you have it assembled. Use the base print to act as a template for the runcam2 hole into the foam through to the bay and also to locate the camera cable tunnel for the foxeer.

You will want to put a small drop of goop or hot glue on the foxeer at the front to hold it to the base print prior to putting on the cover, since the foxeer could move backwards which would not be desired. A drop on each side flush with the face of the base print and just touching the camera body will be enough and easily removable if you have to take out the foxeer for some reason.

title: Dremel Drill Press Mount (just..not for a microscope)

description.text:
Note: If you are looking for a mount that works well for attaching a 12mm microscope to your dremel press, check out this other thing that I've uploaded.

This is a great usb microscope mount for your dremel press... just until you turn your dremel on. I don't think people share enough of their failures, so I'm sharing this just in case the mount might be useful for another purpose (perhaps, as an attachment point for a light?). As it stands, this design wasn't very useful for use as a microscope mount due to the amount of vibration that the dremel transfers into the microscope while its turned on.

This is two components:

  • A 'base' that clips to the side of the dremel press's carriage. It has a really nice, snug fit. This base has a 5mm hole through itself at a 25-degree angle allowing you to insert the 'arm' to point toward the the dremel's target. This bit could very well be useful for other purposes.
  • An 'arm' that is designed for holding one of the common silver USB microscopes you can find on Amazon.

description.text:
As soon as I saw Opossums' Led bridge lamp Universal Segment design, I had to print it!

This remix is the result of issues I encountered while trying to print a few of the original pieces. None of the issues were caused by the original design. The feet and the LED guides and channels have been replaced with custom versions.

Many thanks to Opossums for his original bridge lamp designs!

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200

Infill:

10

Notes:

Supports were only required for the main foot section.

Custom Design Reasoning

This remix is the result of issues I encountered while trying to print a few of the original pieces. None of the issues were caused by the original design. The feet and the LED guides and channels have been replaced with custom versions.

While trying to print the original foot base, I encountered shifting in the x-axis. Repeated attempts resulted in the same issue. I then decided to design my own foot base using Fusion 360 but too encountered shifting in the x-axis. I finally identified the issue as being in the “silent mode” where steps were being missed while printing these large, wide prints, so there really wasn’t any issue with the design. The issue was me!

I decided to stay with my own foot design as I’ve incorporated the option to customize the ends of the foot to support any desired power and other cabling. I also printed the top part of the original foot as a separate piece which is now dimensionally uniform all around. Since the original foot top was not uniform all around, I also had to redesign the extension section (in two pieces) easily rest centered upon the new foot top.

I had issues using the original LED guides and the added LED channels where the tolerances for LED channels were too tight for 10 mm LED strips and while I was able to improve the tolerance with a hacksaw blade, there were then some binding issues with the LEDs passing between LED channel segments due to the angle between the LED segments.

As a result, I decided to design a replacement for the LED guide and channel pieces by combining them into one piece per bridge segment which also reduced the amount of filament used and the need to glue the guides together and then glue the channels to the guides. Since the weight of the bridge segments and led/guides cause the lamp to be a bit unstable, combining the two pieces into one also reduces the weight of the bridge.

In order to redesign the LED guide/channels into one piece, I had to determine the approximate arc of the base of the structural segments where the replacement pieces will reside and used the equation for the chord length below:

C = 2Rsin( theta/2 )

Based on the approximate cord length (C) of 254 mm at the base for two segments and the angle () for two segments where there are 8 segments for 90 degrees, the angle per 2 segments is 22.5 degrees (90/4), thus the radius (R) = 651 mm. While not perfect with the bridge segments, the radius should have been a bit less. The result was an acceptable LED guide/channel design. The LED channels have a profile of 11mm x 3mm and are chamfered at the ends to allow easier threading of the LED strips through the channels.

The STL files used for the revise LED guides:
LED_guide_one_piece_style2 v6.stl

I printed these pieces using Maker Series PETG HD Clear Glass using the following print settings:
Layer height: 0.2 mm
First layer height: 0.2 mm
Perimeters: 5
Horizontal shells: Top: 2 Bottom: 2
Infill 0%
Fill pattern: Rectilinear
Top/bottom fill pattern: Rectilinear
Brim: 4 mm
Supports: none

The customized STL files used:
Blank_Plug_Style2 v3.stl
BridgeBaseMama v4.stl
BridgeBasePapa v3.stl
ExtensionBase.stl
ExtensionMain_WithHole.stl
ExtensionMain_WithOutHole.stl
FeatherPlatform.stl
foot_redo_style5 v3.stl
FootTop.stl
LED_guide_one_piece_style2 v6.stl
PermaProtoPlatform.stl
Power_USB_Plug_Style2 v3.stl

In the end, only the following original STL files were used:
LBLUC-segment_asembly_helper.stl
LBLUC-segment_set.stl
LBLUC_foot_mountingPiece_papa.stl (only the three “pegs” were printed)

All other parts were printed with PLA, generally using the following parameters:
Layer height: 0.2 mm
First layer height: 0.2 mm
Perimeters: 3 or 5
Horizontal shells: Top: 3 Bottom: 5
Infill 10%
Fill pattern: Cubic
Top/bottom fill pattern: Rectilinear
Brim: none
Supports: none (except for foot_redo_style5 v3.stl)

All parts were sliced using Slic3r (Prusa Version).

Note that some of the files need to be rotated in the slicer before slicing and generating g-code.

I lost track of how much print time was involved but estimate maybe 200 hours. Each main foot (foot_redo_style5 v3.stl) alone completed in 31h27m using Slic3r’s default print speeds.

Had I to redo this project, I would certainly probably do some design changes as this noob learned more about Fusion 360’s features.

I would also suggest printing in a filament a bit more flexible than PLA. Attempting to connect/disconnect segments after the LED channels have been glued in can cause the tabs to break off.

Be sure to leave the 3M adhensive tape backing on the LED strips. I would also suggest allow for extra LEDs in your strips and to slide in your LED strips as you combine a segment to other segments.

All in all, I learned a great deal about modeling using Fusion 360 and 3D printing using Slic3r and the Original Prusa I3 MK2 3D Printer, not to mention patience!

A Fritzing diagram and Arduino code demonstrating the LED programmability are included with this remix.

Major Electronic components:

Adafruit Feather HUZZAH with ESP8266 WiFi
https://www.adafruit.com/products/3213

Adafruit Adalogger FeatherWing - RTC + SD (optional, used for Local MQTT Network Control)
https://www.adafruit.com/products/2922

On/Off Switch with White LED
https://www.adafruit.com/products/917

https://www.adafruit.com/products/610
or
http://www.frys.com/product/1922653?site=sr:SEARCH:MAIN_RSLT_PG

74AHCT125 - Quad Level-Shifter
https://www.adafruit.com/products/1787

Tactile Switch Button (optional, used to reset microcontroller)
https://www.adafruit.com/products/1119

Adafruit Perma-Proto Half-sized Breadboard PCB
https://www.adafruit.com/products/1609

Individually addressable WS2812B led strip (60 leds/m), bought 2-5m strips
http://s.aliexpress.com/JNVB7Zbu

ALITOVE 5V 15A AC to DC Power Supply Adapter
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01LXN7MN3/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o07_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

description.text:
Wanted a probe spool for my HeaterMeter probes that could be stacked on itself to keep all my probes together. This design consists of one base part which is printed once per probe, and and end cap which completes the final chamber. The base parts are symmetrical so they can be rotated 180 degrees (alternating probes) or have the probes stack up on each other. Stacking up on each other allows them to trap the probe wire to prevent it from unraveling completely.

Tested with:

  • Maverick ET-72/73 and ET-723
  • Thermoworks ProSeries

The Maverick fit a bit tight, the Thermoworks are a bit loose. In the OpenSCAD file, there are build plates defined for printing 1-4 probes at once.

Updates:

  • 2017-Jul-18
    • Fixed slight effective diameter mismatch between hub round and flat parts causing bump in printed output.
  • 2017-Apr-16
    • Added gap between layers by removing a bit of the probe holster, configurable with probe_cut
    • Removed dependency on OpenSCAD 2016+, no longer uses rotate_extrude(angle)

title: Jeep CJ5 3 Speed Shift Knob Two Color

description.text: I made this part for my 1971 Jeep CJ5. I needed a shift knob and actually having the shift pattern on it would even be better. The hole for screwing it onto the shifter is not threaded as the threads are very fine and I doubt they would print well anyway. I measured the diameter of the shifters threaded end and found it to be .291 inches at the bottom of the threads, so I printed this with a .290 hole and simply screwed it onto the shifter. It was pretty tight but not as tight as I wanted it so I took it off and added a bit of superglue to the hole. It's very tight now. I also gave it an acetone vapor treatment to give it a nice shine. The shift pattern is placed slightly to the left to make it more visible to the driver.

A Farm House version of the cereal box house by Dadhoc.
This is the 5th house for what should become a 'Cereal City' with different styles of architecture. Feel free to be inspired and create your own. View the other designs at my collection.
In this design I wanted to try a few new things, like the roof, studs and the rotating blinds. Take and re-use any cardboard box, make holes on the right spot using the stencils and fix the doorframe and windows using the brackets. If the cardboard layer is to thick you can use some glue to hold the windows.

Use the stencils to cut holes and cut openings for door and windows.
You can use one stencil for all the windows.
Make the holes first before cutting the window openings. I used layer height of 0.25 and a slow speed on the brackets.

description.text: I had an old crate sitting around, and my son had toys strewn all over his floor while he was watching Sponge Bob on Netflix. Being the kinda guy that I am, I saw an opportunity. So I did some quick sanding on the box, hit it with a blow torch (to bring out the grain), then stained and sealed it (2-in-1 stain and polyurethane), hit amazon for a continuous hinge and 2 100nm cabinet openers, 4 pieces of scrap wood painted black, and then opened up tinkercad. Grabbed this padlock by "Meximelt" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1582810, and this jolly roger by BY_CRC http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:123685 and smushed them together. Then cobbled some squares and circles together for corner pieces and the latch assy. I painted them gold and after they were dry I sprayed some black then wiped gently with an alcohol damped rag and attached them with furniture/leather tacks. note the loop that the lock hangs on had to be glued on. I'm no carpenter by any stretch of the imagination, and this was my first attempt at mixing 3d printing with wood, so if a chuckle head like me can do it, so can you! Let me know if I can help you with your project.

title: Minimalistic Tevo Glass Clip

description.text:
I have been using the small binder clips to hold the sheet of glass down to the heatbed, but today while installing an aluminum plate, I noticed that the LPA fan duct was hitting the rear clips, thereby raising the x-axis gantry the smallest bit, throwing off the levelness. Boy, talk about a run on sentence! lol

I made these to solve that problem - only to find out that my glass is FAR from level. Anyway, these are designed with 3mm glass in mind, but you can scale them up or down to fit your particular application. I would suggest 60-100% infill for strength... they're small so the higher infill shouldn't use any negligible amount of filament.

comments.text: These work well. The gap is just a tad too wide for my bed+2.5mm glass, but I simply put a piece of masking tape to take up the difference. Now they're just the right amount of snugness. I'm glad to get rid of the clunky binder clips. Thanks! (Posted in the Made section, too!)

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/8yd84EZ10GA

This is a tatting shuttle that prints as a single body. No assembly required. You will need to sand it to make it smooth enough for its purpose, which is to make lacework.

I've printed it in ABS. It probably will print well in PLA, perhaps easier than with ABS.

Enjoy!

You'll need to finish this with sandpaper.

After breaking off the supports, there will be nubs that need to be sanded out. Even without that, you'll want to sand the shuttle just to get it smooth. Maybe you'll want to paint it too, since bare 3D materials are a bit boring.

the other shuttles found here are in two pieces

I printed out some other shuttles from Thingiverse that are perfectly fine. Probably the world does not need this contribution. But those shuttles all are in two pieces, some using force-fit and others requiring glue to put them together. I didn't see why that should be necessary, especially since printing the other shuttles in the best orientation for strength and utility ends up requiring supports, so may as well print as a unibody. Thus this model.

I used Fusion360 to create the model, saved as STL, then imported into Meshmixer to create the supports. The resulting STL was exported from Meshmixer.

remixed_from.title: Otto DIY build your own robot

description.text:
These were Christmas gifts in various permutations. Finally getting around to making one for myself. Gotten into the 3DLabPrint planes. Those are awesome.

Added arms to the base OTTO DIY design, use the latest Otto feet, legs, head, etc for yours. These are just accessories if you will.

Built a base and top display and storage case for it. The head just barely fits over the robots head. You can lock it into place with the eye accessory. I created a bunch of cutouts on some prints.

I made Otto run off an IR remote ( Tolako IR remote kit -https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01EL7I5HC/ ), created cases for the remote and embossed names into them.

Created a male and a female version of the torso with arms, I'm not sharing those for now, sorry.

I revised the calibration and IR driven smooth criminal code to work with arms as well.

Printing them in PLA on a FFCP2016 directly on a glass bed.

The calibration is HIGHLY recommended. You run the calibration from the serial window like a command line, adjust each appendage with +- Enter commands until it's exactly where you want everything, then back to the main menu, type save and it's saved to EEPROM. Flash the other code back and it will read and use the calibration settings you just set.

title: Spiral Fluted Bowls
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I printed these two bowls on my kit-built FlyingBear P902 printer. These two spiral-fluted bowls both measure 200 mm diameter at the top, 140 mm diameter at the base, and are 100 mm tall. Note that the STL models are solid; that is, in the STL models, the bowls are not hollowed out. To print them as bowls, you MUST use the 'spiralize' or 'vase-mode' settings in your slicer. This setting will not print any infill or top to the bowls, but will print a bottom. (If you are not sure how to use the 'spiralize' or 'vase-mode' settings in your slicer, a search on Google will direct you to a number of instructional sites as well as videos.)

My printer has a 0.4 mm nozzle. I printed my bowls using Cura 2.4 as the slicer. Besides turning on 'Spiralize Outer Contour' under the 'Special Modes' setting, I used a layer height of 0.3 mm, and a line width of 0.6 mm. The bottom thickness was set to 0.9 mm. In this version of Cura, I also had to set 'Outer Wall Wipe Distance' to 0. (This was to work-around a bug in the 'spiralize' setting in Cura 2.4 that causes a small z-hop after each 'layer'.)

My two bowls were printed with transparent blue PLA filament. I designed the actual models in an old version of Alibre 2012. (This software is now called 'Geomagic Design'.)

I do not believe that these bowls will hold water; I noticed on my prints, there seemed to be small leaks at the base of the bowl.

As I stated at the beginning of this description, the bowls measure 200 mm diameter at the top. If the build area of your printer is smaller than this, you can just use the scaling function of your slicer to reduce them in size.

If you have any questions about these two bowls, post them in the comments and I will do my best to answer.

description.text:
ModiBot was designed for SLS printing in Polymide, but we are working toward making him more printable at home. This is the latest offering of parts pre-configured for printing on desktop home printers. We've modified the designs to include integrated supports, so these items should be printed using 'No Supports' settings.

For best results, print in PLA (or ABS, possible) on high detail settings on any home or hobby printer.

Find out more about building with ModiBot at ModiBot.com

Origin:
FDMFlexM-F.stl was modified from FDMShoulder.stl by Kidmechano
FDMFlexF-FZ.stl was modified from FDMForeArm.stl by Kidmechano
FDMFlexF-FC.stl was modified from FDMForeArm.stl by Kidmechano
FDMFlexF-FR.stl was modified from FDMForeArm.stl by Kidmechano
FDMFlexF-FL.stl was modified from FDMForeArm.stl by Kidmechano
FDMFlexM-M.stl was modified from FDMTorso.stl by Kidmechano

Changes: The parts were shortened or altered to act as an additional flex joint to be inserted into the elbow or knee (or anywhere, really) and allow for additional range of motion. This will unfortunately alter Mo's proportions.

Note: If at any point Kidmechano wishes these parts removed, they shall be removed. Additionally, if Kidmechano wishes these part to be acquired/absorbed/incorporated into ModiBot Mo, he is free to do so with or without notice or permission, since the original parts these are based on were his designs (and these parts will then be removed due to redundancy).

In all honesty, since Kidmechano made the originals, he could reproduce these in a superior way from his original files, plus keep them updated.

Check out and support ModiBot.

description.text:
The Black Hole Spinner: a well balanced, eye catching spinner for the fidgety engineer.

This is my first shot at designing a fidget spinner and after doing a number of prints, I am quite pleased with it. It's well balanced, versatile, and eye catching.

I included two versions: one with a fillet around the outer edge, one without. Both look great when finished.

It's compatible with 608 bearings of any type, but I highly recommend the Bones Red bearings. I cleaned mine out with WD40 followed by a an isopropyl alcohol bath and got it to spin for about 1 minute 30 seconds. The bearings can be pressed in with a vice (I used a Pan-A-Vice for mine). Once there in there, they stay put and are unlikely to come loose unless you're hit by a truck. Do not tap the bearings in with a hammer, especially if you choose to print in PLA. Seriously, DON'T DO IT.

If you have any suggestions, drop me a comment. I'm always open to constructive criticism. Stay fidgety!

author: jcatx

description.text: baby toy happy sun spinner

Introduction - Block Models

Training geology students how to understand the intersection of complicated geological surfaces and complicated topography can be challenging.

Simple concepts such as the "Rule of V's" can be taught with simple block models that allow students to see and understand how a dipping layer can make identifiable patterns on the Earth's surface.

Therefore, there is a long history of using wooden blocks to demonstrate everything from relatively complex structural geology to very simple cases.

These models can be purchased, or made by hand.

3D printing provides the opportunity to construct lesson-specific block models, and to create an inexpensive custom classroom set of models that can be integrated in a basic geology curriculum.

Instructions

Opening the Customizer allows you to upload a 100x100 pixel PNG image that is transformed from a greyscale image to a heightmap and placed as the upper layer of a block model.

Settings allow you to change the location, thickness, strike, and dip of the dipping layer, and generate a block model that suits your needs. A vertical scaling parameter is added to enable the adjustment from a greyscale image to something more resembling the topography that you input.

A few notes on using the Customizer

The greyscale images can either be real DEM data (like the Jotunheimen example file) or created in a drawing/paint program using grey gradient fills to represent topography. It is possible to invert the colors in the Customizer, so it doesn't matter whether you use darker or lighter colors to represent highs/lows.

Currently, the Customizer only supports strike angles from 0-90 degrees and dips from 0-90 degrees. To generate the two models included as examples, the greyscale image was simply rotated 180 degrees to enable the beds to dip the other way.

To preview how the dipping layer will fit with your topography, change the drop-down menu at the base of the Customizer to show "Remainder of model only". Note: Be sure to change this back to "Both parts" before clicking the "Create Thing" button to ensure that all necessary parts of the model are made by the script.

What is included here?

Besides the OpenSCAD code for the Customizer, there are several additional files included:

Two block models generated using the Customizer using the included files - these are the 'simplest case' of a valley and dipping bed aimed at teaching the "Rule of V's", similar to the simple wooden block models shown above:

  • Dipping_Upstream_Part1.stl
  • Dipping_Upstream_Part2.stl
  • Dipping_Downstream_Part1.stl
  • Dipping_Downstream_Part2.stl

Also included is a .zip archive containing several example PNGs that can be used immediately in the Customizer:

  • Valley_Heightfield_clean.png - used to generate the "Dipping_Downstream" model
  • Valley_Heightfield_clean_rotated.png - used to generate the "Dipping_Upstream" model
  • Valley_Heightfield_noisy.png - a version of the above with 3% gaussian noise added to simulate some topographic surface roughness
  • jotunheimen.png - an example of real DEM data in greyscale of the glacial valleys of the Jotunheimen area of Norway

How to print the models?

These models would typically require the use of a dual-extrusion printer, and can be printed in a variety of materials.

It is of course also possible to print the pieces individually and glue them together as well!

What next?

This Customizer has a limited strike/dip range, a limited resolution, and the ability to only add a single layer. The OpenSCAD file could be changed to increase the strike/dip range and to add more layers, and to possibly even add folded layers. However, the uploaded image resolution is constrained by Customizer to 100x100 pixels.

Improvements to the OpenSCAD model are strongly encouraged! This is meant to the be the start of a tool, not the end!

Good luck, and rock on!

Creators

This Customizer was the result of a conversation at the AGU Fall Meeting in 2016, and an eventual collaboration between Sinan Akciz (Cal State Fullerton) and John Thurmond - two people who have both taught geology courses at the undergraduate and graduate level and are keen users and abusers of new technology.

description.text:
A hitch pin for hitch covers. Please do not use this pin for load bearing applications as it will fail. It is designed to hold light weight ornamental hitch covers only. It will fit perfectly into a 16mm hole on a 2" hitch. If you find your hitch has a larger hole, please write to me as I have an 18mm version I have not uploaded.

After printing a hitch cover for my jeep, I realized there was no easy way to attach it to the Jeep. The most elegant way to attach a 3d printed cover is a 3d printed hitch pin! After a few variations, I found this design worked the best. I designed it to fully cover the threads, thus protecting them from road grime. The nut cap is deeper than the bolt threads. When installed, the nut cap will cover the threads.

I use PETG with 100% infil. I print it a little hotter than normal (by about 5 degrees) as I want the layers to bond. This produces a pin secure enough to hold a hitch cover. After a full year of abuse, it still holds strong. Print one nut, one bolt, and optionally 2 washers.

Have fun!

title: Hictop 3DP-18 Top Z-Axis Brace W/ Bearing

description.text:
This is meant for the Hictop 3DP-18 (As far as I know it wont fit other Hictop models). I modified the original braces (Created in Onshape by measuring the original part with a digital caliper.) to allow a bearing to fit since the original design had it freely spin in an acrylic hole. This adds a recessed bearing slot as well as x3 M3 nut slots and screw holes. The screw located inside the part has angled edges to allow screwing by hand with knurled screws. The channel is long enough to fit most screws up to 25mm in overall length. There is a hole opposite the screw hole in the channel that allows an allen key to fit. You will lose 6mm of Z-Axis hight. This part fits skateboard bearings size Z08 (ID:8mm OD:22mm).

This was created in Onshape and sliced through Cura (Slic3r Prusa I3 edition is having issues).

(Apologies for the mess in the pictures I'm in the middle of building my enclosure)

title: Tevo Black Widow Dual Z Mount Plate
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Part of my Black Death Tevo build. Motor mount and endplate for dual Z modification. Replaces the red CNC aluminium piece on the top of the side pillars.

  • Allows unconstraint of the lower lead screw without binding at the glide nut on the X-carriage.
  • Allows for use of second stepper driver to reduce motor stress.

Modification is a work in progress. I'm working on rebuilding the z axis to allow less introduction of z binding/wobble issues I had with the original single belt design. With the original design you are unable to deconstrain the lower lead screw without the belt tension pulling the lead screw out of alignment and introducing a force that tries to flex the lead screw. Also removes the uneven force distribution on the top bearing of the lead screw for better longevty and less maintenance

comments.text: Very cool! I was just considering trying to design something like this, possibly with some oldham couplers on the bottom. Have you been using your BW with the Dual z's? Is it working well?
comments.author: cmstewart

comments.text: I have indeed been using it a lot. Works really well so far. I ended up unconstraining the upper motor end and just making sure the lower was constrained in such a way that the weight of the gantry was supported at all times on the lower bearings. no banding issues at all now
comments.author: cmstewart

comments.text: ok so you've still got the lower lock collars and bearings in place then? I'm very interested in trying this out and any help you could provide would be much appreciated!
comments.author: CJay9209

comments.text: yes that's it exactly - the weight of the x gantry is more than enough to ensure that the lead screws with the collars always rest on the lower bearings. I found that with the lower constrained and the motor end completely unconstrained other than with the motor coupler itself, I get way smoother prints. With the upper constrained and the lower unconstrained i found i had far more of an issue with unbalanced forces due to the tolerance requirement being far too much for what I was able to (or willing to) engineer the bracket for. the couplers allow for enough movement that any binding is negated and the collars on the bottom ensure no z travel on the leadscrew itself. I've also had zero issues with z going out of sync since day one.
comments.author: cmstewart

comments.text: Excellent, thanks for the info! May I ask, are you using a Y cable, or the extra port on the Gen to drive the second motor?
comments.author: CJay9209

comments.text: I've actually completely redone the electronics and wiring and used a Rambo 1.3l. It has a dedicated dual z output and digital pots so it's a fair bit different to the original motherboard. I have however used the MKS with the second extruder output as the z axis output on another machine. Keeps the driver way cooler and makes tuning the pot way easier as each motor is independant. Never been a fan of y connectors for the stepper
comments.author: cmstewart

comments.text:
Cool. I've replaced the stock extruder on my machine with a Titan Aero, so I've taken the gearing off of the stock extruder stepper and plan to use that as my second z motor. There's a geared shaft on that motor though, so at first I'm going to try printed oldham couplers to attach the motors to the leadscrews, so I can re-design one of the 5mm holes to fit the geared shaft. If that doesn't work out I'll either replace the shaft on the motor or just buy a new one, and possibly get actual metal flex or oldham couplers to replace the printed ones down the line. Then I guess I'll have to swap the second extruder port on the gen to a second z port in firmware, and make sure the vref on that stepper driver is correct.
Thanks very much for all your help! I'm going to start printing parts now and I'll post some make pics once everything's back together.
comments.author: CJay9209

comments.text: You mean you added a second Z stepper to the original design using one plus belt and pulley ?
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text: No this uses one z stepper for each lead screw directly connected. No need for any pulley or belt. You actually remove th original belt and pulleys for this as it's a direct drive system.
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text:
It is what I thought.
Therefore, you reintroduced the basic Prusa design error that Tevo fixed with its single Z stepper plus pulleys on the Z lead screw. !
comments.author: CJay9209

comments.text: I had nothing but problems with the single stepper design the belt introduced too much inconsistency in smaller z layer values and in afdition strained the driver too much for my liking. Provided you use a decent control board the dual z seems to work just fine. Tevos implementation of the design is ok but the driver and stepper they give you for a single z setup are lacking. As far as I can see it's just personal preference really. I like my board nice and icy lol
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text:
Most probably it is because of improperly tensioned belt, excessive torque required due to misalignment and/or wheels.
Two steppers are prone to get out of synch mainly during power on/off and/or in case of excessive torque required. It is worse if connect in // on one driver. Most people don't realize this, they just level the bed, then at some point it binds. Put marks on both couplings to see if overtime their relative position change. It is in multiple of 4 steps, not much in term of Z travel but overtime it can accumulate or not. But as you know, errors never cancel each others :-)
It is why I modified my Geetech for one Z, eliminating plenty of other issues at the same time. My Z stepper a Nema 17 40mm is even too powerful, because everything runs smoothly. I adjusted the current to .5A as it is enough.
comments.author: CJay9209

comments.text: turst me I've been doing this long enough to know all of that - The dual z is fine - the Rambo has dual z drivers for this very purpose and an isolated power rail for logic,motors and heaters. There's no issues with startup power blips on that board...maybe the original mks base 1.4 but the rambo 1.3l just doesn't do any of the above. As I said I've never had dual z go out of sync for no good reason and provided your frame is aligned right the binding of one lead screw over the other is non existent. The only reason you typically get get z sync issues is when the printer vibrates, the frame flexes or simply shifts which helps bind the z axis on one side. again it's all to do with the setup. like I said I've used this setup on many printers and never had any issues with desync. Personal preference I guess.
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text:
I said "improperly" NOT "over tensioned" belt.
Anyway, steppers are likely to get out of synch even with a separate driver ! It is a open loop system. PERIOD.
An other thing, looks like your lead screws are hanging from the flexible coupling, not from bearings ?
Even here, others have realized it too: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2226464
comments.author: CJay9209

comments.text: The lead screws are secured top and bottom via the bearing and lock-ring design to prevent any vertical translation on the screws...just like the original tevo design, in fact EXACTLY as the tevo design dictates. Now if you want to get really picky (as you seem to be prone to) that design is massively flawed due to the perpensity of the lead screws to deform. One side of the linkage should be unconstrained to prevent the development of binding due to the lateral translation leading to z binding or slight irregularities on layer height. just working on a way to prevent that from happening using the current hardware. might not be possible without he addition of some additional parts. At any rate unconstraining the bottom end to improve z accuracy is a complete waste of time on a single z driven system due to the tension of the belt pulling on one end of the lead screw anyway so it completely and utterly defeats the purpose of improving function either way. In a system using the type of bearings seen in the Black widow, unconstraining the lower end of the leadscrew would allow the belt to pull the belt pulleys medially leading to and overall abduction of the leadscrew increasing friction and binding of the lead screw through the glide nut on the x carriage. Not to mention the excess forces leading to premature deformation and failure of the lead screw.
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text:
I know the Tevo Black widow is not perfect as you said but it could have been improved while keeping one stepper motor.
I also know about the rounding errors, etc...
The point you refuse to consider is that steppers are likely to get out of synch at power on/off !!!! This is a SEPARATE issue that comes in addition to all the other mechanical issues ! PERIOD.
I fail to understand stubborn people like you who can't even do the required search, just get mad, use personal attacks and accuse of trolling.
An interesting reading:
http://www.americanthinker.com/articles/2017/04/k12_fog_and_fuzziness.html
